PetroTerra Corp.: A Paid Promotion That Will Crash And Burn - PetroTerra Corp. (OTCMKTS:PTRA-OLD1) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»PetroTerra Corp.: A Paid Promotion That Will Crash And BurnOct.14.15 | About: PetroTerra Corp. (PTRA) Hunter Straus Long-term horizon, Growth, long/short equitySummaryPTRA is being promoted by the Wall Street Report.The company's balance sheet shows only $2,322 in cash.Insiders own over 50% of the common stock.The company's latest 10-K lists only one employee.I have attempted to contact management regarding the ongoing promotional activity.Background
PetroTerra Corporation (OTCQB:PTRA) has recently been the subject of a series of paid promotional advertisements from Wall Street Report . Most recently, on October 13 and October 11th, promotional emails went out which disclosed that Wall Street Report was being compensated $150,000 for the promotion.
Like nearly all companies that have experienced paid promotions, PTRA has abysmal financials, an unrealistic business plan, and few employees. I believe that PTRA common stock is near worthless, and in the weeks following the promotion, it will be trading far below its closing price of $1.12 on October 13, 2015.
Business and Website
On page F-4 of the company's most recent 10-Q it reads,
PetroTerra Corp. (the "Company") was incorporated under the laws of the State of Nevada, on July 25, 2008. The Company is an independent exploration and development company focused on the acquisition of property (or property leases enabling us to explore and exploit such property) that we believe may contain extractable oil and/or gas. The Company plans to identify, evaluate and acquire oil and gas exploration and development opportunities primarily within the United States. The Company has not generated any revenue to date and consequently its operations are subject to all risks inherent in the establishment of a new business enterprise.
So it's an oil and gas exploration company -- sound straight forward enough. Additionally, the company has a nice, well-manicured website which has a lot of pretty pictures and even a nifty interactive brochure that gives the impression that this is a small, but ambitious little oil and gas exploration company.
However, the company's website hasn't been updated since the beginning of July, yet the stock price has exploded in the absence of any publicized company developments. Surely, if something major happened, the company's PR would want to keep its website updated to inform its shareholders, but there isn't anything new here.

This isn't the only curious thing about -- if we take a deeper look at the company's SEC filings, it's clear that there is a major inconsistency between what appears on the company's website and what is possible in its financial situation.
Financials and Insider Ownership
PTRA's financials are abysmal and indicate that the company is in no position to accomplish any meaningful business goals, and make it impossible to justify its current market cap of $28 million.
The company's balance sheet shows just $2,322 in cash and $737,500 in "oil and gas exploration." Additionally, the balance sheet also shows a Bank Overdraft of $103,970, indicating that the company owes its bank for withdrawing too much cash -- not a good sign.

The Statement of Operations and Statement of Cash Flows are equally depressing, and show a net loss of $93,803 and $117,678 cash used in the company's operations. The company's Statement of Cash Flows also shows that the company received $120,000 from the sale of common stock.


In light of these financial figures, it comes as no surprise that the company's accounting firm as inserted a "Going Concern" statement into page 8 of the most recent 10-Q which reads,

The financial statements have been prepared on a going concern basis which assumes the Company will be able to realize its assets and discharge its liabilities in the normal course of business for the foreseeable future. The Company has incurred losses since inception resulting in an accumulated deficit of $1,461,063 as of June 30, 2015 and further losses are anticipated in the development of its business raising substantial doubt about the Company's ability to continue as a going concern. The ability to continue as a going concern is dependent upon the Company generating profitable operations in the future and/or obtaining the necessary financing to meet its obligations and repay its liabilities, which have arisen from normal business operations as they come due. Management intends to finance operating costs over the next twelve months with existing cash on hand loans from our director and/or private placements of common stock.
If one looks at the Executive Compensation section on page 32 of the most recent 10-K, it shows that the CEO received a salary of $120,000 in 2015. Perhaps this explains why the company plans to continue to fund its operations through the sale of stock, and may explain the company's bank overdraft.
Additionally, the company's latest 10-K filed on June 30, 2015 states that the company only has one full-time employee, and none of the filings since then indicate that the company has gone on a hiring spree. Beyond that, over 50% of the company's outstanding shares are held by the CEO.

Promotion
As mentioned before, PTRA has been promoted through a series of paid promotional emails from Wall Street Report, which also set up a colorful landing page.


A third party identified as "Mass Peak Ltd." disclosed paying $150,000 for the promotional emails. While there is no mention of Mass Peak Ltd in PTRA's filings, it's clear that somebody is trying to create a market, likely in order to unload his or her shares.

Following these promotions, PTRA stock rose from $0.59 at the end of October 9th to close at $1.12 on October 13. Volume increased accordingly, as the average 3-month trading volume of the company's stock is just over 3,800, and just over 791,300 shares were exchanged on October 13.

Most recently, The Wall Street Report promoted Black Stallion Oil & Gas (OTCQB:BLKG), another poorly capitalized entity that has since plummeted from when the promotion came out.
Conclusion
PTRA is yet another example of a paid promotion that touts massive potential for unsuspecting investors, but the product being advertised has no substance. The company's filings have all of the red flags that I could imagine: abysmal financials, hardly any employees, and massive insider ownership.
While there is no certain link between PTRA's management and the promotional activity, it's clear that a major shareholder is looking to unload his or her shares on to unsuspecting retail investors. The stock is worth nearly nothing, and over the course of the next several months, I fully expect that PTRA stock will be trading far below its current price of $1.12.
Disclosure: I am/we are short PTRA. 

